or internus","Originates from the outer surface of the obturator membrane"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe obturator internus is an important hip muscle that has several key anatomical features. The correct answer is that it is \u003Cstrong\u003Einnervated by the nerve to obturator internus\u003C/strong\u003E, which arises from the sacral plexus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EKey anatomical features of this muscle include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EOrigin: Inner surface of the obturator membrane and surrounding pelvic bones\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ECourse: Exits the pelvis via the lesser sciatic foramen\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EInsertion: Greater trochanter of the femur\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EFunction: Lateral rotation of the thigh at the hip joint\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe following statements are incorrect:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInserts on the lesser trochanter of the femur\u003C/strong\u003E - The insertion point is actually on the greater trochanter\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExits the pelvis through the greater sciatic foramen\u003C/strong\u003E - The muscle passes through the lesser sciatic foramen\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFunctions to medially rotate the thigh\u003C/strong\u003E - It performs lateral rotation, not medial rotation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOriginates from the outer surface of the obturator membrane\u003C/strong\u003E - The origin is from the inner surface of the membrane\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The obturator internus muscle arises from the inner surface of the obturator membrane and the adjacent pelvic bones","The obturator internus muscle passes through the lesser sciatic foramen to exit the pelvis","The obturator internus muscle inserts on the greater trochanter of the femur.","The obturator internus muscle is innervated by the nerve to obturator internus, a branch of the sacral plexus.","The obturator internus muscle primarily functions to laterally rotate the thigh at the hip joint."],"references":["Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2018). Textbook of Orthopaedics, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2018). Textbook of Anatomy Abdomen and Lower Limb; Volume II (Vol. 2). Elsevier Health Sciences","Cantrell AJ, Imonugo O, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Leg Bones. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537024/","Raftery A. General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System. Ann R Coll Surg Engl. 2006 Jul;88(4):425. doi: 10.1308/003588406X114802d. PMCID: PMC1964629","Chaudhry SR, Nahian A, Chaudhry K. Anatomy, Abdomen and Pelvis, Pelvis. [Updated 2023 Jul 25]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482258/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67026"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18254"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67026","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67026"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-26T20:34:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-26T20:35:06+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10968"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81726"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api